 Well, FYI, this thing does not exist, I don't have a register,

29
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:59,240
 but these things do stay in my head sometimes.

30
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:05,200
 But we have been hearing that forgiveness is not about just forgetting, right?

31
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:11,920
 And no matter how forgetful you are, there are things that you remember.

32
00:02:11,920 --> 00:02:16,040
 There are things that it is hard for you to let go as well.

33
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:20,160
 There are times for you to struggle with forgiveness.

34
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:25,480
 So what I'm trying to say is, if you find it difficult to let things go,

35
00:02:25,480 --> 00:02:30,400
 you are not alone. I'm like that as well.

36
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:33,800
 These past three weeks, we have been hearing and reflecting

37
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:39,360
 on the importance of forgiveness, how we have been forgiven by God,

38
00:02:39,360 --> 00:02:41,720
 and what forgiveness is.

39
00:02:41,720 --> 00:02:46,240
 And today, we will look into forgiving others.

40
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:50,920
 Before we open the Bible today, I have a question for us.

41
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:57,720
 I wonder, what does it look like when we struggle with forgiveness?

42
00:02:57,720 --> 00:03:02,320
 Those people you need to see regularly, perhaps not someone stepping on your feet

43
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:10,120
 on MTR, but maybe our colleagues, our family members, our friends,

44
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:15,320
 or even our brothers and sisters in the church.

45
00:03:15,320 --> 00:03:20,920
 If they have offended you, how would that impact you?

46
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:25,960
 When you struggle with forgiving them, how would you react?

47
00:03:25,960 --> 00:03:30,520
 And what comes to your mind when you see them?

48
00:03:30,520 --> 00:03:33,280
 Do you just hide your thoughts, hide your emotions,

49
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:37,640
 and try to act normal in front of people?

50
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:41,040
 Do you try to avoid these people?

51
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:47,640
 Or would you want to exclude them from your circle?

52
00:03:47,640 --> 00:03:54,240
 For me, if someone offends me, I would definitely go to the avoidance side.

53
00:03:54,240 --> 00:03:57,040
 If you offend me, I don't want to see you.

54
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:02,680
 If I see you in a pantry, I will not get water until you walk out the pantry.

55
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:06,440
 If I see you in the lower house, I would probably go to the upper house.

56
00:04:06,440 --> 00:04:08,160
 But actually, I don't get to decide.

57
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:15,120
 And if I see you in my family dinner, I would try to get the furthest seat I can

58
00:04:15,120 --> 00:04:18,160
 just to avoid talking to you.

59
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:23,720
 I wonder if you can resonate with any of these.

60
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:27,320
 But this is not what God intend us to be, right?

61
00:04:27,320 --> 00:04:31,840
 Especially when it happens in our church community.

62
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:40,080
 We are brothers and sisters, and we are all part of the same body of Christ.

63
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:47,520
 So today, we will look into the forgiveness within the church body in our early church.

64
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:52,880
 Last week, Derek shared one of the biblical examples of forgiveness with us,

65
00:04:52,880 --> 00:05:00,480
 with Stephen getting stoned, and he released his forgiveness to the people who killed him.

66
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:06,640
 Such a beautiful testimony from one of the followers of Christ.

67
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:13,680
 And I would like to continue to read that passage, the immediate verses after that.

68
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:19,680
 So Acts 7.59, "While they were stoning him, Stephen prayed,

69
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:23,920
 'Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.'

70
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:31,440
 Then he fell on his knees and cried out, 'Lord, do not hold this sin against him.'

71
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:35,680
 When he had said this, he fell asleep."

72
00:05:35,680 --> 00:05:41,520
 And immediately after this, "And Saul approved of their killing him.

73
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:46,880
 On that day, a great persecution broke out against the church in Jerusalem,

74
00:05:46,880 --> 00:05:53,760
 and all except the apostles were scattered throughout Judea and Samaria.

75
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:59,280
 Godly men buried Stephen and mourned deeply for him.

76
00:05:59,280 --> 00:06:05,360
 But Saul began to destroy the church, going from house to house.

77
00:06:05,360 --> 00:06:10,560
 He dragged off both men and women and put them in prison."

78
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:15,200
 So the scripture tells us that it was Saul who approved the killing,

79
00:06:15,200 --> 00:06:18,640
 and we know that this Saul is the apostle Paul,

80
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:24,720
 who later became an apostle and has done a lot for our church.

81
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:28,400
 "And he killed Stephen."

82
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:32,960
 Stephen is now with Jesus, he does not need to struggle with forgiveness anymore,

83
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:37,600
 and in fact, he doesn't need to struggle with anything anymore.

84
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:45,280
 But how about his brothers and sisters, those who witnessed the killing?

85
00:06:45,280 --> 00:06:51,280
 If we read chapter 6, we can see that Stephen was one of the seven people

86
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:55,920
 whom the twelve apostles appointed to help with the ministry.

87
00:06:55,920 --> 00:07:02,320
 And the scripture describes Stephen as a man full of God's grace and power,

88
00:07:02,320 --> 00:07:08,000
 performed great wonders and signs among the people.

89
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,680
 Such a faithful brother that they have lost.

90
00:07:13,680 --> 00:07:18,400
 Those who witnessed would struggle with their emotions,

91
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:21,520
 they mourned deeply for him.

92
00:07:21,520 --> 00:07:25,920
 And there were even more and more people getting imprisoned and killed

93
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:30,240
 by the Jews and Saul.

94
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:36,160
 How would the church community feel towards the Jews and Saul in this case?

95
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:39,920
 Sometimes when we read this passage, we go too fast into,

96
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:44,720
 "Oh, he's the apostle Paul, has done so much for Jesus later,

97
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:49,680
 wrote so many letters that we are still reading today."

98
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:57,280
 And it's true that he's a great apostle that built up the foundation of our faith.

99
00:07:57,280 --> 00:08:02,880
 But perhaps sometimes we miss the perspective from other disciples at that time.

100
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:06,400
 In their eyes, in the church's eyes at that time,

101
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:12,800
 he is a murderer who killed a lot of Christians.

102
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:16,480
 And he is an oppressor as well.

103
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:24,000
 If I were one of them, if I personally witnessed that my friends are getting killed by a person,

104
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,600
 this is something that I will always remember.

105
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:35,280
 And I would definitely struggle with forgiving them.

106
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:38,720
 So,

107
00:08:38,720 --> 00:08:46,480
 but we remember that in the past weeks that we can't rely on our own strength to forgive people.

108
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:52,240
 This is the good news for us. We don't need to do that by ourselves.

109
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:56,240
 And God's work in people are amazing.

110
00:08:56,240 --> 00:09:05,200
 As we continue to read, we can see how God moves the people in the early church to forgive in this case.

111
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:13,120
 "Now there was a disciple in Damascus named Ananias, and the Lord said to him in a vision,

112
00:09:13,120 --> 00:09:17,760
 'Ananias,' and he said, 'He I am, Lord.'

113
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:23,280
 And the Lord said to him, 'Get up and go to the street called Strait,

114
00:09:23,280 --> 00:09:32,080
 and inquire at the house of Judas for a man from Tarsus named Saul, for he is praying.

115
00:09:32,080 --> 00:09:39,920
 And he has seen a vision, a man named Ananias came in and lay his hands on him,

116
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:43,280
 so that he might regain his sight.'

117
00:09:43,280 --> 00:09:49,920
 But Ananias replied, 'Lord, I have heard from many people about this man,

118
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:54,000
 how much harm he did to your saints in Jerusalem.

119
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:01,840
 And here he has authority from the chief priests to arrest all who call on your name.'

120
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:08,000
 But the Lord said to him, 'Go, for he is a chosen instrument of mine,

121
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:13,520
 to bear my name before the Gentiles and kings and the sons of Israel,

122
00:10:13,520 --> 00:10:19,600
 for I will show him how much he must suffer in behalf of my name.'

123
00:10:19,600 --> 00:10:28,000
 So Ananias departed and entered the house, and after laying his hands on him, he said,

124
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:35,280
 'Brother Saul, the Lord Jesus who appeared to you on the road by which you were coming,

125
00:10:35,280 --> 00:10:43,040
 has sent me so that you may regain your sight and be filled with the Holy Spirit.'

126
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:50,560
 And immediately something like fish scales fell from his eyes, and he regained his sight,

127
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:57,920
 and he got up and was baptized, and he took food and was strengthened.

128
00:10:57,920 --> 00:11:06,560
 So we can see that when Ananias hears about the idea of going to find Saul and laying hands on him,

129
00:11:06,560 --> 00:11:09,200
 he was unsure about that.

130
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:16,160
 Saul was literally still on his way to persecute the church before his conversion.

131
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:22,560
 The danger is real before we even talk about forgiveness in this case.

132
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:27,680
 And we can see that Ananias was subtly against this idea.

133
00:11:27,680 --> 00:11:35,360
 See how he called Saul 'this man', not even addressing his name.

134
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:46,080
 But God explains his plan to Ananias, that Ananias has a role in God's work as well.

135
00:11:46,080 --> 00:11:50,800
 His role is to redeem Saul's life, so in the future,

136
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:56,400
 Saul can proclaim Jesus' name to Gentiles and other people.

137
00:11:56,400 --> 00:12:01,200
 So we are under the Gentiles category, right? Most of us.

138
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:10,720
 Can we imagine what happens to us if Ananias disobeyed God at the moment?

139
00:12:10,720 --> 00:12:13,600
 Would we even exist?

140
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:19,600
 I'm sure God has his own way to work that out if Ananias refused to do that.

141
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:29,120
 But thankfully, Ananias chose to obey, and he is willing to be part of God's work.

142
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:35,200
 I want us to pay attention to how Ananias addresses Paul when he gets there.

143
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:42,480
 The first word he said is, "Brother Saul, this is powerful.

144
00:12:42,480 --> 00:12:47,920
 From this man to brother."

145
00:12:47,920 --> 00:12:52,080
 Ananias knows his assignment.

146
00:12:52,080 --> 00:13:01,040
 The way that he calls him 'brother' demonstrated forgiveness and also full acceptance to Saul,

147
00:13:01,040 --> 00:13:08,240
 that he has included Saul into the church community, which is essential.

148
00:13:08,240 --> 00:13:13,440
 Because Jesus could have healed his eyes, healed Saul's eyes in his own way.

149
00:13:13,440 --> 00:13:15,760
 He doesn't need to send people there.

150
00:13:15,760 --> 00:13:22,800
 But Jesus chose to send someone to do that, to be part of his work.

151
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:27,280
 Have we thought about why?

152
00:13:27,280 --> 00:13:32,800
 God intended his people to be accepted in his community.

153
00:13:32,800 --> 00:13:36,960
 No matter what terrible things we have done in our life,

154
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:44,800
 and no matter how unworthy we feel we are, we are all accepted.

155
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:54,320
 Jesus sends Ananias to Saul to accept him before he even proves that he is a worthy Christian.

156
00:13:54,320 --> 00:13:56,640
 This is powerful.

157
00:13:56,640 --> 00:14:02,000
 Because how can Saul convince the acceptance of the forgiveness of God

158
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:08,080
 if he didn't experience that from other Christians?

159
00:14:08,080 --> 00:14:15,120
 However, being accepted by Ananias does not mean that the whole community has accepted him.

160
00:14:15,120 --> 00:14:16,640
 Yet.

161
00:14:16,640 --> 00:14:21,440
 I want to continue to read the story as I want us to know that

162
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:26,080
 it was uneasy for the early church community as well.

163
00:14:26,080 --> 00:14:31,040
 It takes time for the community to go through the forgiveness journey.

164
00:14:31,040 --> 00:14:37,760
 And different people would have their own pace, would have their own journey on that.

165
00:14:37,760 --> 00:14:41,040
 Just like you and me.

166
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:49,200
 When he, he is Saul, came to Jerusalem, he tried repeatedly to associate with the disciples.

167
00:14:49,200 --> 00:14:57,200
 And yet, they were all afraid of him, as they did not believe that he was a disciple.

168
00:14:57,200 --> 00:15:03,760
 But Barnabas took hold of him and brought him to the apostles and described to them

169
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:09,200
 how he had seen the Lord on the row, and that he had talked to him,

170
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:15,760
 and how he had spoken out boldly in the name of Jesus at Damascus.

171
00:15:15,760 --> 00:15:25,600
 And he was with them, moving about freely in Jerusalem, speaking out boldly in the name of the Lord.

172
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:30,560
 And he was talking and arguing with the Hellenistic Jews,

173
00:15:30,560 --> 00:15:34,800
 but they were attempting to put him to death.

174
00:15:34,800 --> 00:15:43,760
 Now when the brothers learned of it, they brought him down to Caesarea and sent him away to Tarsus.

175
00:15:43,760 --> 00:15:51,520
 So the scripture tells us, emphasizing that he repeatedly tried to associate with the disciples,

176
00:15:51,520 --> 00:15:54,240
 but they were afraid of him.

177
00:15:54,240 --> 00:16:03,040
 We can see that Saul's repentance and conversion did not immediately lead to forgiveness

178
00:16:03,040 --> 00:16:06,320
 and acceptance from the whole community.

179
00:16:06,320 --> 00:16:08,800
 People still remember what he has done,

180
00:16:08,800 --> 00:16:14,400
 and probably still wrestling with the loss that they have experienced.

181
00:16:14,400 --> 00:16:20,240
 How would they trust this murderer immediately?

182
00:16:20,240 --> 00:16:27,360
 It indeed takes time and people's effort to encourage forgiveness in the community.

183
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:35,360
 But here we've got a Barnabas who didn't only offer his own forgiveness to Saul,

184
00:16:35,360 --> 00:16:42,400
 but also to help Saul to be forgiven by other people.

185
00:16:42,400 --> 00:16:49,440
 Barnabas put in effort in helping the community to see what has happened in Saul

186
00:16:49,440 --> 00:16:57,520
 and more importantly to see Saul's new identity as a Christian, as a follower of Christ,

187
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:02,800
 and to help Saul to be accepted by the community.

188
00:17:02,800 --> 00:17:07,680
 And forgiveness does not mean that what Saul has done is forgotten.

189
00:17:07,680 --> 00:17:15,680
 In fact, what he has done is remembered forever, as it is recorded in the Bible.

190
00:17:15,680 --> 00:17:21,200
 But forgiveness is letting go of our sense of being wronged and offended,

191
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:29,840
 and to see the person in God's sight, to see them from God's perspective.

192
00:17:29,840 --> 00:17:38,160
 And this act, this act of forgiveness, is to fulfill God's work in our community.

193
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:44,720
 And at the same time, I want us to see that Saul also takes his ownership of his actions.

194
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:48,480
 Firstly, he didn't force others to forgive him.

195
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:56,160
 He didn't say to other Christians, "Oh, you are a Christian. You're supposed to be gracious.

196
00:17:56,160 --> 00:18:01,840
 You're supposed to be merciful. You're supposed to be forgiving."

197
00:18:01,840 --> 00:18:07,040
 These words sound familiar, right? But Saul didn't do it.

198
00:18:07,040 --> 00:18:10,880
 Also, if we read the letters he was writing to the church,

199
00:18:10,880 --> 00:18:14,800
 he has not been hiding the things that he has done.

200
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:21,520
 He takes responsibility of his own sins and actions.

201
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:30,000
 And it is important that we know that it is by the grace of God that he has been forgiven.

202
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:35,040
 Forgiven by God, and forgiven by others.

203
00:18:35,040 --> 00:18:39,120
 Church, this is a reminder to us as well.

204
00:18:39,120 --> 00:18:45,520
 If we have wronged others, take responsibility of our own actions.

205
00:18:45,520 --> 00:18:50,720
 Ask for forgiveness with the posture of asking grace.

206
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:57,360
 For us who need to forgive others, we are not only doing that for the sake of our mental health.

207
00:18:57,360 --> 00:19:03,600
 There's something more. We are doing the work of God.

208
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:10,160
 Ananias, with his obedience, becomes part of God's plan to redeem Saul's life

209
00:19:10,160 --> 00:19:17,520
 so that he can become the apostle Paul that God intends him to be.

210
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:23,840
 And Barnabas and the whole community works together on their forgiveness with Saul.

211
00:19:23,840 --> 00:19:31,120
 Together, they have demonstrated the forgiveness of Jesus to Saul.

212
00:19:31,120 --> 00:19:37,760
 This is the church. This is who we are.

213
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:42,800
 Starting with a strong foundation of forgiveness.

214
00:19:42,800 --> 00:19:49,120
 Perhaps today in this room, we don't have an apostle Saul for us to redeem,

215
00:19:49,120 --> 00:19:58,320
 but will we lay down our preferences and rights to fulfill God's work within our community?

216
00:19:58,320 --> 00:20:01,840
 I want to share a little bit of my personal story as well,

217
00:20:01,840 --> 00:20:08,720
 which I took a long time to forgive the people in my church community as well.

218
00:20:08,720 --> 00:20:13,040
 It happened in my uni time. I was not in this church yet.

219
00:20:13,040 --> 00:20:20,320
 I was part of a young adults community, just like 180 here, similar.

220
00:20:20,320 --> 00:20:23,440
 So one time we were planning for an event together,

221
00:20:23,440 --> 00:20:26,640
 and then the communication was bad. It was terrible.

222
00:20:26,640 --> 00:20:31,600
 And the event did not turn out as we wished.

223
00:20:31,600 --> 00:20:37,200
 So it ended up like the organizers were having a conflict among us.

224
00:20:37,200 --> 00:20:39,920
 So for sure, I was part of that conflict.

225
00:20:39,920 --> 00:20:46,800
 And then people in our community heard of this conflict among the organizers,

226
00:20:46,800 --> 00:20:49,760
 and people started to take sides,

227
00:20:49,760 --> 00:20:55,040
 which we know is unhelpful when we are involved in a conflict.

228
00:20:55,040 --> 00:20:56,960
 But we were young, right?

229
00:20:56,960 --> 00:21:00,160
 It wasn't that of a big deal at the beginning,

230
00:21:00,160 --> 00:21:07,280
 but things got worse, and then we get to a point that we can't really resolve it.

231
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:14,960
 So just as I said in the beginning, if I get offended, I will avoid the people.

232
00:21:14,960 --> 00:21:20,560
 So that's what I did. I stopped showing up to my community gatherings.

233
00:21:20,560 --> 00:21:26,880
 And then later, I felt, "Oh, I still want a community."

234
00:21:26,880 --> 00:21:33,360
 I made an even worse decision that I joined another community in the same church.

235
00:21:33,360 --> 00:21:37,920
 My church wasn't that big, just a few hundred people, so we all know each other.

236
00:21:37,920 --> 00:21:41,440
 It was very weird that we show up in the same church,

237
00:21:41,440 --> 00:21:44,800
 but I just went to another community.

238
00:21:44,800 --> 00:21:48,400
 But I am quite stubborn, if I'm honest.

239
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:52,000
 So I did that for almost half a year,

240
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:58,560
 until someone from my original community came to me and told me that,

241
00:21:58,560 --> 00:22:05,440
 "Jennifer, you know what? We missed you, and we want you to come back."

242
00:22:05,440 --> 00:22:08,400
 At the bottom of my heart, I wanted to do that as well,

243
00:22:08,400 --> 00:22:14,960
 but at that time, I was not brave enough to do the conversation that I need to do,

244
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:18,640
 to forgive what has happened, to forgive the people,

245
00:22:18,640 --> 00:22:23,600
 and at the same time, ask for their forgiveness.

246
00:22:23,600 --> 00:22:26,480
 So I was being immature for a few more months,

247
00:22:26,480 --> 00:22:31,840
 and then finally, I got myself together and felt, "I really want to go back."

248
00:22:31,840 --> 00:22:38,480
 So in that period, more people came and asked me to go back,

249
00:22:38,480 --> 00:22:41,760
 to encourage me, "You can do it."

250
00:22:41,760 --> 00:22:46,000
 They are like Barnabas and Ananias in my situation,

251
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:51,520
 to help me to go back and have conversation with the people.

252
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:54,240
 So at the end, I did that, I went back,

253
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:57,440
 and then I have the conversation with my community,

254
00:22:57,440 --> 00:23:00,400
 and we all lay down what has happened,

255
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:04,480
 and continue to have fellowship together.

256
00:23:04,480 --> 00:23:09,760
 From this experience, I personally experience the power

257
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:16,560
 of both forgiveness and also unforgiveness in a church community,

258
00:23:16,560 --> 00:23:23,200
 and how a few people's actions can impact the whole community.

259
00:23:23,200 --> 00:23:28,400
 Well, the honest truth is, as long as we are in community,

260
00:23:28,400 --> 00:23:32,640
 as long as we are with people, conflicts will happen,

261
00:23:32,640 --> 00:23:35,280
 and we will need to forgive.

262
00:23:35,280 --> 00:23:41,840
 For Saul as well, after him being accepted, became an apostle,

263
00:23:41,840 --> 00:23:43,040
 he still has conflict.

264
00:23:43,040 --> 00:23:48,080
 He had a conflict with Mark later, and then it leads to splitting,

265
00:23:48,080 --> 00:23:52,880
 and even more conflicts within the early church community.

266
00:23:52,880 --> 00:23:56,560
 But later, they sort that out, the relationship,

267
00:23:56,560 --> 00:24:05,200
 and then both Mark and Paul are having important roles in the early church.

268
00:24:05,200 --> 00:24:11,680
 So what I'm saying is, as long as we are in the community,

269
00:24:11,680 --> 00:24:13,520
 we can't really avoid conflict,

270
00:24:13,520 --> 00:24:17,920
 we can't really avoid the conversation of forgiveness.

271
00:24:17,920 --> 00:24:22,400
 Earlier this year, we have gone through the Ephesians series,

272
00:24:22,400 --> 00:24:23,920
 which is written by Paul.

273
00:24:23,920 --> 00:24:28,560
 There's a passage that Paul writes his reflection about forgiveness.

274
00:24:28,560 --> 00:24:30,320
 Let me read it to you.

275
00:24:30,320 --> 00:24:34,640
 "Get rid of all bitterness, rage, and anger.

276
00:24:34,640 --> 00:24:39,920
 Brawling and slander, along with every form of malice.

277
00:24:39,920 --> 00:24:43,200
 Be kind and compassionate to one another,

278
00:24:43,200 --> 00:24:49,760
 forgiving each other, just as in Christ God forgave you."

279
00:24:49,760 --> 00:24:55,520
 We see, this is Paul's reflection after all the things that had happened in his life.

280
00:24:55,520 --> 00:25:00,640
 It is essential for the church community to forgive one another,

281
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:05,120
 as the sense of unforgiveness will birth into something else

282
00:25:05,120 --> 00:25:08,960
 that will harm the whole community.

283
00:25:08,960 --> 00:25:10,560
 And forgiveness is hard.

284
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:15,600
 It's not as simple as just saying, "I forgive you," to each other.

285
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:17,600
 But it is a hard work.

286
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:21,600
 We need to do that from the bottom of our heart.

287
00:25:21,600 --> 00:25:25,760
 And there are things that it's really difficult to handle.

288
00:25:25,760 --> 00:25:29,360
 Things like people that broke your trust,

289
00:25:29,360 --> 00:25:31,600
 people who betrayed you,

290
00:25:31,600 --> 00:25:34,560
 or even people who abused you.

291
00:25:34,560 --> 00:25:38,960
 And again, if you are in an abusive situation,

292
00:25:38,960 --> 00:25:44,400
 do seek help from the people you trust.

293
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:47,120
 But what I'm saying is,

294
00:25:47,120 --> 00:25:51,600
 "I forgive you" does not have the magical power

295
00:25:51,600 --> 00:25:54,720
 to heal all the wounds that are in your heart.

296
00:25:54,720 --> 00:25:57,760
 It takes time, and it takes effort,

297
00:25:57,760 --> 00:26:04,000
 and it takes God's grace for us to do the forgiveness.

298
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:08,480
 I'm not sure what you are going through right now,

299
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:10,560
 but you are not alone.

300
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:18,400
 You don't need to do this alone if you are struggling with forgiveness.

301
00:26:18,400 --> 00:26:22,080
 If you are struggling with forgiving people,

302
00:26:22,080 --> 00:26:23,200
 again, this is hard.

303
00:26:23,200 --> 00:26:25,760
 It takes time and effort to do that.

304
00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:30,240
 But do ask for God's grace and strength to do that.

305
00:26:30,240 --> 00:26:36,400
 He is with you, and only by His power we can do that.

306
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:39,280
 And if you have offended someone,

307
00:26:39,280 --> 00:26:43,520
 if you need to ask for forgiveness,

308
00:26:43,520 --> 00:26:46,160
 take responsibility of your own action.

309
00:26:46,160 --> 00:26:49,360
 Go find the people that you have offended

310
00:26:49,360 --> 00:26:52,000
 and ask for their forgiveness.

311
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,880
 Make known of your heart to the people

312
00:26:54,880 --> 00:26:57,280
 and ask genuinely.

313
00:26:57,280 --> 00:27:04,080
 And ask again for God's grace and strength to do that.

314
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:05,360
 And for some of us,

315
00:27:05,360 --> 00:27:11,680
 we might be the people that are seeing the struggle of forgiveness around us.

316
00:27:11,680 --> 00:27:16,240
 If you are walking with people on that,

317
00:27:16,240 --> 00:27:19,200
 let's come around the people who struggle

318
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:22,960
 because they need the community to help them.

319
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:26,400
 Be like Barnabas or Ananias,

320
00:27:26,400 --> 00:27:31,680
 that help people, to encourage people to forgive.

321
00:27:31,680 --> 00:27:34,240
 To come around them, to support them,

322
00:27:34,240 --> 00:27:38,400
 because it is a long journey.

323
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:39,840
 Do not take sides.

324
00:27:39,840 --> 00:27:44,640
 I'm saying this from my very painful experience.

325
00:27:44,640 --> 00:27:48,880
 Try to see the things in God's perspective.

326
00:27:48,880 --> 00:27:54,080
 And try to see that we are doing the work of God.

327
00:27:54,080 --> 00:27:59,920
 And we are doing this together as one body.

328
00:27:59,920 --> 00:28:03,120
 And this is like we are called the body of Christ

329
00:28:03,120 --> 00:28:07,840
 to demonstrate who Jesus is to the people around us.

330
00:28:07,840 --> 00:28:10,320
 So let's demonstrate the love of Christ

331
00:28:10,320 --> 00:28:15,200
 and the power of forgiveness as this is to fulfill God's work.

